{
  "text": "The assessment of spatial dimensions is an essential part within integrated disaster risk management; however, this has so far often been neglected in respective academic efforts (M\u00fcller-Mahn 2013) . Understanding the spatial patterns of vulnerability, as well as the geographical limits of their trigger, and the development of appropriate management strategies is crucial in disaster risk management, both risk reduction measures prior to an event and response and recovery efforts [CITATION_1] . While patterns of exposure are basically evolving on all spatial scales and are often subjected to short-term and longterm dynamics, changes in vulnerability usually rather occur on a longer term such as changes in regional population or economic characteristics. Therefore, vulnerability is critically context dependent [CITATION_2] , and variable patterns of vulnerability determine where and when a mere natural event potentially turns into a disaster.",
  "citation_candidates": [
